Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the final session of the day! The players are out in the middle. Tamim Iqbal and Mahmudul Hasan Joy will open the batting for Bangladesh. Duanne Olivier will begin with the new ball. Three slips and a gully in place. Let's go!
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

Bangladesh can breathe a sigh of relief now! After toiling hard for 5 sessions they have finally managed to grab all ten wickets and wrap the innings up. Taijul Islam was the leader of the pack, he grabbed 6 wickets and was disciplined as well. Khaled Ahmed also bowled well and he was rewarded with 3 wickets for his bowling. The pitch is still assisting the batters and Bangladesh will want to go on till the end of the day without losing any wickets. Do join us for the final session of the day!

It's been a scintillating batting performance from South Africa! There were contributions from all the players. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee started off well, it was carried on by Keegan Petersen and Temba Bavuma and eventually finished by Keshav Maharaj. He played a fiery knock of 84 and guided them over 400 runs. But they have posted a huge total and they have plenty to bowl at now. South Africa will be hoping they can grab a couple of wickets in the final session and put Bangladesh under pressure early on.

OUT! LBW! Mehidy Hasan finally gets one wicket. An arm ball, sliding from round the wicket on middle. Williams gets low and looks to sweep but misses and gets hit near the front pad. An appeal and up goes the finger. Lizaad Williams takes a review for formality as that looked plumb. Ball Tracking shows wickets hitting and that will be the end of South Africa's inning. They are all out on 453. That will be Tea on Day 2!

Bangladesh started off well, they did trouble the batters early on with some swing, and Khaled Ahmed was rewarded with the wicket of Kyle Verreynne. But since then, it's been only South Africa! They were leaking runs after the drinks break. Once again, Taijul Islam and Khaled Ahmed have been the pick of the bowlers for Bangladesh. Taijul Islam broke the partnership between Keshav Maharaj and Wiaan Mulder with a peach of a delivery. We could see the ball turning sharply towards the end and Bangladesh will be looking to come back and wrap the innings up. However, the pitch is still assisting the batters. Let's see what the second session has in store. The post-Lunch session is set to begin at 4:10 pm IST (10:40 am GMT). Do join us then!

Session 1 - Overs - 25, Runs - 106, Wickets - 2. Bangladesh will be pleased since they managed to grab a wicket at the stroke of Lunch, but the session has still belonged to the hosts. After losing Kyle Verreynne, Keshav Maharaj and Wiaan Mulder put together around 80 runs and guided South Africa to a score of 380. Maharaj came out to bat with some intent and started scoring runs at a brisk rate and he brought his 4th Test fifty within no time. Wiaan Mulder did perish just before the Lunch break, but that will not matter much, South Africa have already got a healthy total on the board and anything from here will be bonus runs!

The surface is a bit two-paced, It was not spinning much but it will start turning later on, but all in all a good surface. Taijul Islam is up for a chat. He says he feels very happy, the last time he played was against Pakistan but it was a long time ago and he just keeps himself ready. Tells that the quicker ball comes faster on the bat so he was bowling with the conditions.

Dean Elgar, Keegan Petersen, and Temba Bavuma all scored a half-century while Sarel Erwee and Ryan Rickelton perished after getting a good start. The second new ball is around 8 overs old and it is still relatively new, and the pacers will look to take advantage of it. Stay tuned for further updates.

Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 2 between South Africa and Bangladesh. The match is still in the early stages and there is nothing to separate them at the moment. You might say the host are slightly ahead, just slightly because they scored at a very good rate but not taking away anything from the tourists who came back strong in the final session of Day 1.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

The skipper, Dean Elgar, after choosing to bat first, made justice by scoring runs at a brisk rate. He was well supported by Sarel Erwee but he fell. After that, Keegan Petersen and Bavuma came in and both of them got to their half-centuries and they failed to go big. All in all, South Africa will be pleased with the way they have played. They still have 5 wickets in hand while the way Bangladesh folded things up, they will be happy too. A decent day of cricket with both teams sharing it. Day 2 promises to be an intriguing one and it will start at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). Do join us early for the build-up as well. Cheers!

Session 2 - Overs - 30, Runs - 92, Wickets - 2 . A pretty evenly poised session. South Africa might have lost two wickets in the session, but they still continue to remain in a commanding position. Dean Elgar and Keegan Petersen started scoring runs freely at the start of the session. But Elgar perished soon, after a fine knock of 70. Bavuma along with Petersen put together 51 runs. However, Petersen also failed to convert his half-century into a big one and was dismissed soon after the rain break. There was some assistance for the bowlers early on and Bangladesh did try their best to create any chance. There was an LBW chance early on but Bangladesh did not review it. Ahmed took the wicket of Erwee but after that, there was nothing much for the tourists. Bangladesh are giving away runs too easily and they'll hope to keep things tight in the second session that will begin at 4.10 pm IST (10.40 am GMT) Do join us then!

Session 1 - Overs 28 - Runs 107 - Wickets 1 - South Africa are in the driving seat at the moment. They are scoring at a brisk rate with good intent and it is the skipper, Dean Elgar who took the charge from the start. Erwee was also looking good but his stay was cut short. Petersen has played some beautiful shots and the pitch is currently favouring the batters, not completely but enough for them to notch up big runs which South Africa will eye for.

We are ready for action! The players are out in the middle. They will all take the knee in support of the BLM movement. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee will open the batting for South Africa. Khaled Ahmed will begin the new ball. Three slips and a gully in place. Let's go!
The players are in the middle and they have lined up for their respective national anthems. First, it will be Bangladesh's anthem followed by South Africa's.

PITCH REPORT - Shaun Pollock says that spinners are going to get assistance, there is grass coverage but it's a bit patchy, and it is much drier this time. Adds that the length can be a touch short, and pacers might get some reverse-swing as well. He says that the batters will need to use their feet well here, or else they will get trapped in the crease as the bounce will be lower.

Mominul Haque, the captain of Bangladesh, says that they have to make a strong comeback with the bat after what happened in Durban. mentions that he thought they played the first four days well. Informs that they would have batted first as well had they won the toss. States that they have two changes- Taijul in place of Taskin and Tamim in place of Shadman.

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa, says they will bat first as the pitch looks dry and with two spinners, they need a good start. Informs they are playing the same XI and he is working on a bit of consistency as a leader. Tells that they can be more aggressive as a seam bowling unit, it's important for someone to notch-up a three figure score with the bat. Tells many people would have written them off but it's been a brilliant run so far. Mentions they have one more Test and it's so important for them to win, especially with the World Test championships. Informs there is nothing to worry about his stitches on his forehead.

Bangladesh (Playing XI) - Tamim Iqbal (In for Shadman Islam), Mahmudul Hasan Joy, Najmul Hossain Shanto, Mominul Haque (C), Mushfiqur Rahim, Liton Das (WK), Yasir Ali, Mehidy Hasan, Taijul Islam (In for Taskin Ahmed), Khaled Ahmed, Ebadot Hossain.

South Africa (Unchanged playing XI) - Dean Elgar (C), Sarel Erwee, Keegan Petersen, Temba Bavuma, Ryan Rickelton, Kyle Verreynne (WK), Wiaan Mulder, Keshav Maharaj, Simon Harmer, Lizaad Williams, Duanne Olivier.
TOSS - South Africa have won the toss and they have elected to BAT first!

The hosts put on an all-round performance and won the game quite convincingly. Not to forget, they put on a dominant show without many of their keys players. They will want to replicate the same performance and try to clean-sweep Bangladesh in the series. Which team will dominate Day 1 of this Test? We will find out. Stay tuned for the toss and other updates.

The visitors fought hard in the first four days of the first Test but they just gave it all away at the end. They were absolutely bamboozled by the South African spinners and were dismissed for just 53 runs. But we all know how dangerous Bangladesh can be. They have defeated New Zealand in New Zealand earlier in the year and they have also managed to come on top against South Africa in the ODI series. They are well and truly capable of turning things around in the second Test.

Hello and welcome folks! It’s time for the second and final Test between South Africa and Bangladesh at St. George’s Park. After four days of tough Test cricket, South Africa wrapped the first Test within the first hour of Day 5. It was an exceptional bowling performance from them to take a 1-0 lead in this series. Bangladesh will look to leave their wounds behind from the first Test and come back stronger and try to get over the line this time.
... SECOND TEST ...
We are back for the third innings of this Test! The players are out in the middle. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee are the openers for South Africa.  Ebadot Hossain to start with the ball.
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Not the best batting display by Bangladesh! The pitch was assisting the batters on Day 2 but Bangladesh did not capitalize on that. Tamim Iqbal did get to a good start but he failed to go till the end, and by the end of the day they had lost half their side. Mushfiqur Rahim and Yasir Ali put on a solid partnership in the first session on Day 3, but once that partnership was broken. It was all going downhill for Bangladesh. The pitch is assisting the bowlers now and Bangladesh will be hoping they grab quick wickets and not let South Africa get away with a healthier lead.

What a complete performance this has been from South Africa! After putting a healthy total on the board, the bowlers were right on cue with the ball. They have bundled out Bangladesh for 217 runs and have a lead of 236 runs. They had to toil hard to grab wickets in the first session. But they made sure, the Bangladesh tail did not wag for too long and wrapped things up quickly after Lunch. Duanne Olivier and Wiaan Mulder grabbed 5 wickets together on Day 2, and today Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer took the remaining 5 wickets. They had an option of enforcing follow-on, but South Africa will come out to bat again!

Commentary.Howout: c Lizaad Williams b Simon Harmer

We are back for the second session of the day! The players are out in the middle. Taijul Islam and Mehidy Hasan will resume their batting. Simon Harmer will begin with the ball. A silly point, short leg, and two slips in place. Here we go...
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

Bangladesh still trail the first innings score by 243 runs while South Africa have done well to remove both the overnight set batters. Mehidy Hasan is the only known batter and he needs to keep on batting to reduce the deficit. Bangladesh will hope for a big partnership between Hasan and Islam. An exciting second session coming up. Do join us at 4.30 pm IST (11.00 am GMT).

Session 1 - Overs 29 - Runs 71 - Wickets 2 - A hard fought session for Bangladesh and the wicket of Rahim at the brink of Lunch will hurt them. With two wickets, it will be South Africa who will enjoy Lunch more. The hosts were expected to come out hard again with the ball but the moisture made it hard for them to put pressure. Ali started the day with intent and was dealing in boundaries. He grew into the game nicely but so did the bowlers of South Africa, Wiaan Mulder, and Duanne Olivier were consistent in their bowling while Maharaj found his rhythm as the game progressed. Harmer was not used throughout the session but he was brought late into the attack and got the prized wicket of Mushfiqur Rahim.

Wiaan Mulder is down for a chat. He says that in the context of the game, they are in a good place. Mentions that the team wanted him to get runs and he is happy to contribute and he is pleased with picking up wickets. States that he wanted to bowl at the stumps, but he did not bowl as well to right-handers as he did to the left-handers. He was keeping it fuller to the left-handers and attacking the stumps.
The conditions are gloomy and very dull, and it was also raining overnight. The floodlights have already been switched on. However, we should be able to start on time. Stay tuned for further updates!

Pitch Report - There was rain overnight but there is still good covering of grass and the conditions are perfect for bowling. The seamers will enjoy the condition but the spinners will play a key role as well.

The visitors are in a spot of bother. They have lost half their side and are still trailing by 314 runs. Mushfiqur Rahim and Yasir Ali were troubled a lot by the spinners but they did well to survive till the end. But things are only going to get tougher for them since it’s not going to be as easy to bat on. We have an intriguing first session coming up stay tuned!

South Africa ended Day 2 in a commanding position. After an exceptional batting performance, they were right on cue with the ball as well. Duanne Olivier and Wiaan Mulder caused a lot of trouble with their swinging deliveries and managed to grab 5 wickets. We did witness the spinners getting a lot of spin towards the end and coming into Day 3 they will be the ones causing problems to the batters.

Hello and welcome back, folks to the final Test of this entertaining series between South Africa and Bangladesh. We are now heading towards Day 3 which is known as the moving day and by the looks of it, we could get to know in which direction is this match headed.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

The last session saw spinners getting some purchase and there was a great amount of turn. It is expected to stay the same on Day 3 and it will not be a good sign for Bangladesh, since they are already 5 down. Rahim showed his experience and made sure no more damage is done. 10 wickets fell on Day 2, five from either side. Day 3 promises to be more entertaining and it is all set to begin at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT), but do join us in advance for the build-up as well. Till then, cheers!

South Africa will be going back to bed pretty relaxed after their brilliant performance throughout the day. It was with the bat first, they added 175 runs, all thanks to Keshav Maharaj's wonderful performance. Mulder, Simon Harmer, and Williams played superb cameos and helped South Africa end the first innings with a mammoth score of 453. The momentum was with them and they continued their good work with the ball. It was the pacers though that troubled Bangladesh with the swing. Duanne Olivier early on and then it was Wiaan Mulder who troubled the left-handers with his probing lines and lengths. Bangladesh were ready to tackle the spinners but pacers came out of the syllabus. There was a good partnership between Iqbal and Shanto of 79 but nothing after that.

... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Bangladesh did well to grab 6 wickets in the middle, but they have a mountain to climb now. Mehidy Hasan and Taijul Islam were the bowlers that grabbed 5 wickets and were causing trouble. So we could see the pitch is assisting the spinners, and batting on this wicket is not going to be easy. Bangladesh will need a miracle to chase down this target. Bangladesh do have around 10 overs in the day left. Can they survive this phase without losing any wickets?

South Africa have declared! Well, everyone saw that coming! The way the batter were scoring, the declaration was around the corner. But they have a mammoth lead of 412 runs now. Once again, all the batters have chipped in with a vital few runs and have given the bowlers plenty to fight for now. South Africa did lose 6 wickets but that did not matter much, since the scoring rate was always good. South Africa do have around 30 minutes of play left in the day. How many wickets can they grab?

OUT! TIMBER! The ball hits the stumps and Dean Elgar from the balcony calls both the batters back. Declaration from South Africa and they lead by 412 runs. The ball goes onto rattle the off stump.

... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

Bangladesh's tailenders did not add many runs at the start of the session and they were sent back to the hut quickly by the spin duo of South Africa. Coming into bowl, they did leak runs at the start, but they fought back with two wickets. It's once again, Taijul Islam who has caused trouble and has been rewarded with the wicket of Dean Elgar and Keegan Petersen. The pitch is assisting the spinners for now and things will get tougher for Bangladesh once they came out to bat again. Will South Africa declare today? We will find out. Stay tuned for the final session of the day! The third session begins at 6:50 pm IST (1:20 pm GMT). Do join us then!

SESSION 2 - Overs - 24, Runs - 91, Wickets - 5. Plenty of action in this session! But it's South Africa that continues to remain in the driver's seat! After coming to bat again, Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee started scoring at a brisk rate. However, Dean Elgar perished soon, and Keegan Petersen was also dismissed just at the stroke of Tea! However, Sarel Erwee is still at the crease and he is looking pretty comfortable for now. They already have a healthy lead of 320 runs, and they do have plenty of time and wickets in hand to add more runs. South Africa will be looking to add quick runs and put Bangladesh to bat once again. It will be interesting to see when they declare.

OUT! LBW! A huge appeal for LBW and up goes the finger! Petersen has a chat with Erwee and takes the review. UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Right then! That is all we have from this exciting series. Dean Elgar collects the trophy and he joins his teammates to celebrate the victory. Bangladesh clinched the ODI series, while South Africa put in a domination show and have managed to seal the Test series. It's been tough Test series for Bangladesh, but they still do have positives to take from this tour. Alright then, with this we are done with yet another series, but there is still a lot of cricket happening around. You can keep checking the fixture page for all the upcoming matches. Until we meet again, it's goodbye and cheers!

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa, says that it's been a good few months since he has taken over the captaincy. Mentions that Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer just had to trust the process, and luckily the conditions did favour them, but overall they have been exceptional and Maharaj continues to be his No.1 spinner. States that they have a good core and a good group going forward, Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer are leading the way for them. Informs that the attitude of the younger guys and the lower-order adding runs impressed him a lot. Concludes by saying that they have a  good team now, and a lot of options that will help them in the upcoming tours away from home.

Keshav Maharaj is the Player of the Match and Player of the Series as well. He says he is really happy as his team crossed the line. It was a clinical performance in all departments. Adds that Elgar and the coach had a chat with him and appreciated him and told him to continue doing the right things. Mentions that he repeats the process, just a few little tweaks but he is happy to get the reward. Tells that he doesn't look at the stats, he will look at it at the end of his carer. On Harmer, he says he is a world-class bowler and he is working hard and hopes he gets his reward as well. Says that with the bat, he middle some shots but was disappointed not to get the triple-digit.

Mominul Haque, the skipper of Bangladesh says he thinks they didn't play well as a team in both the matches, and he is disappointed but they also have to look forward. Adds that they play really well as a team but there was no partnership with the bat or the ball. Tells that they should be able to play in any condition in international cricket. Mentions they have to focus on the process, they were thinking of the result here rather than the process.
Time for the presentation...

Dean Elgar decided not to enforce follow-on and they went out there to bat again and added quick runs. The intent was clear from them, they wanted to add quick runs, declare and grab a few wickets at the end of Day 3. That's exactly what happened. They got a lead of over 400 runs, declared, and managed to take three wickets at the end of Day 3. Coming into Day 4, South Africa bundled out Bangladesh for just 80 runs and clinched the series convincingly. Not to forget, South Africa have put a dominating performance in the full series without many of their key players. While Bangladesh failed to perform as a team and will be disappointed with their show.

It all started with South Africa putting up a mammoth total of 453, with all the batters making vital contributions. Dean Elgar, Keegan Petersen and Temba Bavuma notched up their half-centuries and Keshav Maharaj was the one who scored the most runs in the first innings. He scored 84 runs and guided South Africa over 400. Bangladesh came into bat and were troubled a lot by the seamers. They lost the first five wickets to the seamers and the last 5 to the spinners. Tamim Iqbal, Mushfiqur Rahim and Yasir Ali did put on a fight with the bat and they failed to go till the end. South Africa ended with a healthy lead of 236 runs. With all the batters contributing and most of the bowlers grabbing a wicket, it was a complete team performance for South Africa.

7 wickets for Keshav Maharaj and 3 wickets for Simon Harmer, the story was the same in the first Test as well. Bangladesh had no answers whatsoever. The spin twins, have wrapped up the Test match just within 1 hour of the first session on Day 4. Bangladesh batters were all over the place, a few of them just gave their wickets away in trying to play big shots, while others were simply bamboozled by the spinners.

SOUTH AFRICA WIN THE MATCH AND SEAL THE SERIES! They have continued their domination in the second Test as well, and once again it's their spinners who have created havoc and have demolished Bangladesh's batting line-up. Not to forget, it was their batters first that piled up over 400 runs and gave the bowlers a lot to fight with. After a historic ODI series win, it's been a disappointing Test series for the visitors.

South Africa had a good first innings score after they bundled out the tourists and they added another 176 runs at a quick rate and took the lead past the 400-mark. What do we expect on Day 4? Well, we saw the spinners start the proceedings with the red cherry and there was a good amount of purchase for them and just like the previous game, we could expect the spinners to finish the game. With all the momentum by their side, South Africa will hope for early inroads and bundle Bangladesh as soon as possible while Bangladesh will hope that atleast their skipper, Mominul Haque shows some determination with the likes of Mushfiqur Rahim and put on a good fight. Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 4 between South Africa and Bangladesh. The hosts are in pole position right now with just 7 wickets away from the win. South Africa gave a small tricky period for Bangladesh to handle on Day 3 but they lost three quick wickets and are looking fragile as they were seen in Durban in the previous match. They will need a miracle to save this Test match.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Bangladesh need 386 runs to win with 7 wickets in hand and with plenty of time left. Spin twins, Keshav Maharaj, and Simon Harmer are already at work with the new ball, boy, it is spinning sharply. It will be a tough day for Bangladesh but surely an entertaining one for us. Day 4 will commence at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). Do join us in advance for the build-up as well. Till then, Cheers!

The day started with Bangladesh batting and ended with the same as well but with a whole different scenario. Rahim and Ali started the day with intent and played really well to cut the first innings score but once they both fell, Bangladesh were bundled out for 217. South Africa had a lead of 236 runs at that time and they added another 176 to stay in the commanding position. Dean Elgar declared the innings and asked Bangladesh to bat for a tricky period. They did it but in a cause of losing three wickets.

The new batsman will join on Day 4 as the umpire calls STUMPS on Day 3. Phew! A 'moving day' indeed! So many things have happened on this day and it is fair to say, South Africa are well ahead in the game. They need 7 wickets to win with an ample amount of runs to defend. Keshav Maharaj just loves to bowl when his team is in a winning position and he has shown that yet again as he has already grabbed two wickets of Bangladesh who had to tackle a very tricky period. Tamim Iqbal's wicket at the stroke of stumps was a pinch of salt to their wound as his wicket has made things even more difficult for them.

Tosses it up, full again, around middle. Mominul Haque blocks it out off the front foot.
Fuller ball, around middle. Mominul Haque leans and defends it out.
Loopy ball, full, outside off. Mominul Haque guides it towards third man for a brace.
Pitches it up again, outside off. Mominul Haque pushes it towards mid off.
Full, around middle and leg. Mominul Haque flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Full, around middle. Tamim Iqbal leans to flick this but the ball goes off the outside edge towards point.
FOUR! Loopy delivery, full, outside off. Tamim Iqbal leans and drives it past cover for a boundary.
Short again, outside off. Tamim Iqbal pushes it towards cover.
Shorter ball now, around off. Tamim Iqbal defends it out off the back foot.
Loopy ball, outside off, fuller in length. Tamim Iqbal defends it out.
Fuller ball, outside off, spinning away. Tamim Iqbal leans to block this and but he gets beaten.
Full and on off. Blocked out.
Sharp turn again. Haque misses his defensive shot and gets hit on the pads.
Tossed up, on off, spinning back sharply. Haque prods to defend but misses and the ball goes to the left of leg slip who catches it one handed. There was no bat on it.
Around off, drilled down to long on for a single.
Maharaj keeps bowling outside off. Iqbal gets inside the line and blocks it out.
Too full and on middle. Iqbal prods and defends it to the leg side.
On middle. Blocked out.
Floated this time, outside off. Haque gets low and guides it to point.
A flighted ball, tailing on the pads. Haque keeps it out on the leg side.
Full and on off. Haque drives it to covers.
Touch fuller and this time Haque blocks it out.
This one lands on off and spins away sharply. Haque looks to defend on the front foot but misses.
Outside off. Iqbal blocks it out.

CHANCE! Full and outside off, again sharp turn there. Iqbal steps across to block it but gets an inside edge and the ball balloons behind short leg and in front of square leg. Both run towards the ball and both leave it for each other. Okay, there was no bat there.
FOUR! Iqbal will not mess around, he will be aggressive as much as he can be! Tossed up, on middle. Iqbal slog-sweeps it behind square on the leg side for a boundary.
Full and turning on middle. Haque flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Mominul Haque the skipper of Bangladesh, comes to bat now.

OUT! LBW! Maharaj with an absolute beauty of a delivery! On a length and outside off, it lands and spins back in sharply. Shanto steps across and looks to defend but gets beaten by the turn there. He gets hit on the pads and a sharp appeal follows. The umpire raises his finger and South Africa celebrate but Shanto takes the review. He thinks that might go onto miss the leg stump but Ball Tracking shows it is the umpire's call on wickets hitting. Bangladesh are already in a lot of trouble and it is Keshav Maharaj who is making it difficult for them!
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Keshav Maharaj

Commentary.Commentary: Review! Najmul Hossain Shanto has reviewed an LBW decision! There is no bat involved there. Ball Tracking shows it is the umpire's call on wicket's hitting! Najmul Hossain Shanto has to walk back.
Flatter, on a length and on middle. Iqbal rocks back and wrists it to deep square leg for a single.
Darted on the pads. Shanto flicks it in front of square on the leg side for a couple.
On middle. Blocked out.
Two byes! This one lands on off and spins away sharply with some serious bounce. The keeper fails to collect it and two runs are taken.
Flatter and outside off, Shanto gets his pad in the line.
Tossed up, on off. Shanto keeps it out on the off side.
On middle, fuller and Shanto comes forward to block it.
Will it be spin from the other end? Yes, it will be! Simon Harmer comes into the attack.
Slightly short and on middle. Shanto tucks it to square leg for a single.
Around off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Ohh, almost another wicket! Full ball, and outside off. Shanto looks to drive but gets an inside edge past the leg stump and to fine leg for a boundary.
Najmul Hossain Shanto walks out to bat at number 3.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Keshav Maharaj loves to bowl in the fourth innings! Tossed up, on a length and around off, this one skids through and does not turn much. Mahmudul Hasan Joy leans and looks to defend but gets an outside edge to the keeper who gets a glove on it and the ball deflects to gully where Wiaan Mulder takes it. Mahmudul Hasan Joy nicked it but still was thinking of a review. That will be a pair for Mahmudul Hasan Joy!
Commentary.Howout: c Wiaan Mulder b Keshav Maharaj

Commentary.Commentary: This is full and angling on middle. Iqbal leans to block it but gets an inside edge and o the right of leg slip. A single taken and Bangladesh are off in the chase.
Starts with a full ball, outside off. Iqbal steps across and blocks it out.
